<div class="highlight views-row views-row-1 views-row-odd views-row-first highlight-with-narrow3"><a class="feature-link" href="/publications/dragons-footprints-china-global-economic-governance-system-under-g20-framework"><div class="type">Books</div><h3>The Dragon’s Footprints: China in the Global Economic Governance System under the G20 Framework</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src=https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/feature_square/thedragonsfootprints-square.jpg alt=""/></div>In this book, CIGI&#039;s Alex He takes a close look at China&#039;s rise to become one of the most active and influential players in global economic governance.</div></a></div><div class="top-row feature-block-row" data-columns="3"><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-2 views-row-even narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/publications/agenda-of-german-g20-presidency-global-sovereign-debt-restructuring-regime"><div class="type">Policy Briefs</div><h3>G20 Mission: A Global Sovereign Debt Restructuring Regime</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/istock_86804249_xlarge.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>For the Agenda of the German G20 Presidency, this policy brief explores a consistent and credible regime for sovereign debt restructuring.</div></a></div><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-3 views-row-odd narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/publications/energy-g20-finance-track-g20-energy-transformation-during-german-presidency"><div class="type">Policy Briefs</div><h3>G20 Mission: Energy Transformation during the German G20 Presidency</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/istock_19937666_xlarge.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>Energy should no longer be left primarily to the G20 “Sherpa track,” but should be included prominently in the “finance track”.</div></a></div><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-4 views-row-even narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/articles/g20-exclusive-interview-tom-bernes"><div class="type">CIGI in the News</div><h3>CIGI @ G20: China Daily&#039;s Exclusive Video Interview with Thomas Bernes</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/thomasbernes_0.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>Bernes shares his opinion on China&#039;s role in the global economy from the G20 summit with China Daily reporter Liu Zheng.</div></a></div></div><div class="bottom-row feature-block-row" data-columns="3"><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-5 views-row-odd narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/blogs/kevin-carmichaels-observer/lagardes-hangzhou-message-g20-no-more-excuses"><div class="type">blog</div><h3>CIGI @ G20: Lagarde’s Hangzhou message? No more excuses</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/lagarde_1_1.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>The IMF’s advisory note to leaders was unusually pointed, displaying a sentiment that one rarely finds in official documents meant for public consumption.</div></a></div><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-6 views-row-even narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/blogs/kevin-carmichaels-observer/highlight-of-hangzhou-summit-swan-lake"><div class="type">blog</div><h3>CIGI @ G20: The Highlight of the Hangzhou Summit – Swan Lake</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/hangzhou_0.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>If Lagarde’s best memory of the G20 summit is the gala that President Xi Jinping put on for his guests, then the meeting accomplished little of substance.</div></a></div><div class="feature-block-cell views-row views-row-7 views-row-odd views-row-last narrow-with-highlight3"><a class="feature-link" href="/articles/amid-global-uncertainty-trudeau-has-rare-g20-leadership-opportunity-0"><div class="type">CIGI in the News</div><h3>CIGI @ G20: Canadian Leadership &amp; Saving Globalization</h3><div class="short"><div class="feature-image"><img src="https://www.cigionline.org/sites/default/files/imagecache/user_square_thumb/tom_0.jpg" alt="" title="" width="75" height="75" class="imagecache imagecache-user_square_thumb imagecache-default imagecache-user_square_thumb_default"/></div>The actions that are necessary (to improve economic growth) require some bold political steps that a lot of leaders are not in a position to do" said Tom Bernes</div></a></div></div></div> </div>
